Twenty-seven scientists from the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, the Netherlands, Spain and Malaysia issued a joint statement in the Lancet, denouncing conspiracy theories that COVID-19 pneumonia is not a natural origin.

The statement also expressed support for the efficient work of China's scientific research, public health and medical workers.

Just over the weekend, Republican Party Senator Tom Cotton repeated the coronaviruses origin conspiracy theory in an interview. The Washington Post couldn't stand it, either, writing directly under the headline "Kirton keeps repeating the rebutted new coronavirus conspiracy theory. ".

On February 18th the Lancet website published a joint statement signed by 27 scientists. As researchers in the field of public health, "we have been closely monitoring the situation of the new coronavirus disease COVID-19, " the statement said.

Image Credit: screenshot

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The scientists expressed support for the rapid identification of pathogens by Chinese colleagues and medical personnel, measures to reduce the impact of the epidemic, and the sharing of relevant results with the global health community, "these efforts are commendable. ".

But the rapid, open and transparent sharing of information about the outbreak is threatened by "rumors and misinformation" about the disease's origins, the statement said.

"We strongly condemn the conspiracy theory that COVID-19 did not originate in nature. "

The results of a global analysis of the genome of SARS-CoV-2, the virus that causes the new coronavirus, overwhelmingly confirmed that the virus is like many other new pathogens, the statement said, "from wild animals. ".

The statement noted, in particular, that an earlier letter from the presidents of the US National Academies of Science, engineering and medicine and the scientific community they represented further supported this conclusion.

On February 6, the National Academy of Science, engineering and medicine sent a letter to Kelvin Droegemeier, director of the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy.

At drogmaier's request, the college consulted top experts in virology, infectious disease genomics, genomics, epidemiology and other fields on the origin and development of new coronavirus pneumonia, the letter said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The letter says researchers are studying the relationship between the neocoronavirus and viruses in bats and other species. As of the time of writing, "the closest approximation to the 2019-nCoV is a coronavirus from bat samples collected in China" .

Collecting samples related to the outbreak and "wildlife samples" as soon as possible will help trace the source, according to experts in various fields.

After the outbreak, "synthetic virus" , "virus laboratory leaks" , "the United States launched a virus war" and other rumors and conspiracy theories spread on the Internet.

The scientists'statement in the Lancet reiterated that conspiracy theories only create fear and prejudice and do nothing to help global cooperation in the fight against the epidemic.

"We support the call by the director-general of the World Health Organization for promoting scientific reasoning and solidarity, not misinformation and conjecture. We hope that all those who are working on the front lines in China know that we are with you in this fight against the virus."

The 27 scientists who co-signed the statement include Thewes, a former director of the CDC's Center for Infectious Diseases, and Sai Kit Lam, a prominent Malaysian scientist and a key discoverer of Nipah virus.

"We have a clear conscience, " China's Wuhan Institute of Virology said Wednesday in response to online rumors about synthetic viruses, lab leaks and a graduate student being "patient zero. ".

Just on Sunday, Republican Party Senator Kirton spoke to the Fox News Channel about the lab leaks and the synthetic virus conspiracy theory.

"In response to Kirton's comments, [ and in previous interviews with the Washington Post ] , a number of experts have dismissed the possibility that the virus may have been manufactured, " the Post reported

Vipin Narang, an associate professor at MIT, argues that such unsubstantiated and irresponsible conspiracy theories do not help, "Kirton should be spending more time funding U.S. agencies to fight the virus, not passing the buck. ".

Who director-general Tan Desai has previously warned that conspiracy theories and rumours will only "make the work of our heroic staff more difficult" .
